Australian CPI graphs in FiveThirtyEight style¶

Website FiveThirtyEight has been known for publishing attractive graphs. Their aesthetic style could now be reproduced with Python's matplotlib package via the style feature. I will attempt to create a time series for the Australian CPI index using the matplotlib library and the data from the Australian Bureau of Statistics. The original Excel workbook came with a spreadsheet for the CPIs according to the major cities, and another spreadsheet organised by the consumption category. The two spreadsheets were saved into two separate csv files.

The files could be found at http://www.abs.gov.au/AUSSTATS/abs@.nsf/DetailsPage/6401.0Dec%202017?OpenDocument

It has been known that housing affordability has worsen while the general rate of inflation has been subdued. The economic trend is not even across Australia as some cities such as Melbourne and Sydney are known to have higher standards of living which is reflected by their higher cost of living. This CPI graph will enable us to identify the different trends across the major cities and the different consumption categories.

The data currently has the CPI changes per quarter in terms of percentages. A more accurate measure would be to set a baseline of 100 as the first row and calculate a cumulative sum for each column to find the CPI index realtive to the baseline at 01/06/2005.

This would require a row to be added and the cumulative sum calculated.

In order to graph the time series in chronological order, the period column needs to be converted from a string into a date format.

In [13]:
#Period is currently a string(object) and needs to be converted into datetime format.
import datetime
aus_cpi_types['Period']=pd.to_datetime(aus_cpi_types['Period'],format='%d/%m/%Y')
aus_cpi_types.dtypes
aus_cpi_cities['Period']=pd.to_datetime(aus_cpi_types['Period'],format='%d/%m/%Y')
#Rename the weighted average column in cities.
aus_cpi_cities=aus_cpi_cities.rename(columns={'Weighted average of eight capital cities':'National weighted average'})

Due to some colours being repeated under the default setting, a new set of distinctive colours should be generated for each of the lines. The colour package could generate a series of colour objects and the number of colours should correspond to the number of columns. These colour values could be used for the text labels.

In [23]:
#create a colour list of 12 values that ranges from red to purple
from colour import Color
red = Color("red")
blue = Color("purple")
newlist=list(red.range_to(blue, 12))

After generating the colour specifications from the colour package, the colour values are currently colour objects, which are unreadable by matplotlib. So, the they will need to be converted by selecting the hex attribute of each value.

To create a series of their corresponding hex colours.

In [24]:
#create a colorlist by extracting the hex attribute 
#from the previously generated list of colour objects
colorlist=[]
for i in newlist:
    colorlist.append(i.hex_l)
